            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What is ABV?</h2>
              <p>
                <strong>ABV</strong> stands for
                <strong>Alcohol by Volume</strong>. It is the standard way to
                express how much pure ethanol is present in an alcoholic drink,
                as a percentage of the total volume.
              </p>
              <p>
                For example, a beer labeled <strong>5% ABV</strong> contains
                about 5&nbsp;mL of pure alcohol in every 100&nbsp;mL of beer
                (measured at 20&nbsp;°C).
              </p>

              <h2>ABV formulas used in this calculator</h2>
              <h3>1. Simple OG–FG ABV formula</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>ABV&nbsp;[%] ≈ (OG − FG) × 131.25</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                This classic homebrew formula is quick and works well for most
                standard‑strength beers and ciders.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Advanced ABV formula (more accurate)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >ABV&nbsp;[%] ≈ 76.08 × (OG − FG) / (1.775 − OG) × (FG /
                  0.794)</code
                >
              </div>
              <p>
                This empirical formula better accounts for the changing density
                of the solution as sugar is converted to alcohol and CO₂. It is
                usually closer to lab measurements, especially for stronger
                beers and wines.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Converting Brix / Plato to specific gravity</h3>
              <p>
                When you enter Brix or Plato, the calculator internally converts
                them to specific gravity using:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >SG ≈ 1 + (Brix / (258.6 − ((Brix / 258.2) × 227.1)))</code
                >
              </div>
              <p>
                Plato and Brix are numerically very close for brewing purposes,
                so the same conversion is used.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Dilution and blending ABV</h3>
              <p>
                When you dilute or blend two liquids, the total amount of
                alcohol is conserved:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>Final ABV = (V₁ × ABV₁ + V₂ × ABV₂) / (V₁ + V₂)</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                where volumes are in the same units (L, gal, etc.) and ABV is in
                percent.
              </p>

              <h2>How to use this ABV calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Measure OG</strong> before fermentation with a
                  hydrometer or refractometer.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ferment completely</strong> until gravity readings are
                  stable for at least 2–3 days.
                </li>
                <li><strong>Measure FG</strong> at the end of fermentation.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter OG and FG</strong> in the OG/FG tab and choose
                  simple or advanced formula.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Read the result</strong> and optionally check
                  attenuation and alcohol units per serving.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Typical ABV ranges</h2>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Light beer / session IPA:</strong> 3.0–4.5% ABV</li>
                <li><strong>Pale ale / lager:</strong> 4.5–5.5% ABV</li>
                <li><strong>IPA / strong lager:</strong> 5.5–7.5% ABV</li>
                <li><strong>Imperial stout / barleywine:</strong> 8–12% ABV</li>
                <li><strong>Table wine:</strong> 10–13.5% ABV</li>
                <li><strong>Fortified wine:</strong> 15–22% ABV</li>
                <li><strong>Spirits (vodka, gin, whisky):</strong> ~40% ABV</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about ABV</h2>

              <h3>Is this ABV calculator only for beer?</h3>
              <p>
                No. The formulas work for
                <strong>beer, cider, mead and wine</strong> as long as you have
                reliable gravity or Brix/Plato readings and a complete
                fermentation.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Why do I get different ABV values with different formulas?
              </h3>
              <p>
                All ABV formulas are approximations. The simple formula assumes
                a linear relationship between gravity drop and alcohol. The
                advanced formula better models the changing density of the
                solution. Differences of 0.1–0.3% ABV are normal.
              </p>

              <h3>How does priming sugar affect ABV?</h3>
              <p>
                Priming sugar for bottle conditioning adds a small amount of
                extra alcohol, typically
                <strong>+0.1 to +0.3% ABV</strong> depending on the dose. This
                calculator does not explicitly add priming sugar, but you can
                approximate it by treating the primed beer as Batch 1 and adding
                a small Batch 2 with the sugar’s equivalent alcohol.
              </p>

